<div style="background-color: #0a0a0a; border: 3px solid #bdacd1; padding: 15px; color: #ffffff; box-shadow: 0 0 15px #bdacd1; font-family: Kavivanar;color: white">Content Warning: This level contains heavy themes of judgement and wrongdoing, depicting Backrooms-typical graphic violence and death. In addition, there is a story-style segment that  mentions suicide and multiple sections where an entity directly talks down to the reader. It should also be noted that this page is best read in '''dark mode.'''</div>
<div style="text-align:left">
{{Color|background color=linear-gradient(to bottom,#b4a8c2,#978aa6,#736a7e)|border color=#bdacd1|text=
<div style="font-family:Kavivanar; color: #120a1e">
{{Class Custom Image|header=Survival Difficulty: Class|bg-image=929CustomImage.png|hexagon= |class=4|safety=<span style="color:black";>Mental Hazards</span>|security=<span style="color:black";>Varying Stability</span>|entity=<span style="color:black";>Presence of a Powerful Hostile Entity</span>|color-h=240|color-s=67%|color-l=70%}}'''Level 929''' is the 930<sup>th</sup> level of the Backrooms.

<center><span style="font-family:Pacifico"><span style="color:black; font-size:35px">Description</span></span></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
{{Blurimage|file=929opening.jpg|caption=An image taken within the physical space of Level 929.}}
Physically, '''Level 929''' begins in a manner that is quite serene. It takes the form of a motel lobby floating in the sky, interiorly furnished with warm tones, The walls are painted a shade somewhere between a warm ochre and beige, the carpet is patterned in a manner typical to hotel and motel buildings, and generic paintings of landscapes not dissimilar to those present in [[The Frontrooms|the Frontroom]]<nowiki/>s are often hung on the walls in ornate frames. In terms of furniture, the warm tones continue in upholstered chairs and faux wood coffee tables. The appearance of this level attempts to put up a facade of luxury, but is rather sparsely furnished and barren, and thus fails at achieving the aesthetic and instead falls somewhere in the realm of quiet transitionary space.

As aforementioned, '''Level 929'''<nowiki/>'s traversable space is set floating in a cloud-filled sky, which can be viewed through rooms within the level that have entire walls replaced with windows. Trying to break the thick glass of these windows has been unsuccessful, and further attempts are unadvised as it is unknown what exactly lies below the clouds. One leading theory is that the level floats within [[the Void]], but this is unconfirmed and should therefore be taken with a grain of salt.

The level's diurnal cycle spends most of its time at dawn and dusk, with a dawn-day-dusk-night ratio of 8-4-8-4 in hours. During these dawn and dusk periods, light filters through the clouds in a myriad of colors in a manner that is downright picturesque. The day and night periods are unremarkable and, presuming one has not slept at dusk, should be treated as entirely safe. At dawn, '''Level 929''' becomes a tad more unstable as the Dreamwalker shifts their focus to the Mindscape rather than the physical space, and noclips out or in are significantly more feasible. One should make the most insistent of attempts to exit the level at this time.

<center><span style="font-family:Pacifico"><span style="color:black; font-size:25px">Sleep Anomaly</span></span></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
During the 8-hour dusk period, any wanderer within the level will become overwhelmed with an indescribably intense sense of fatigue. This fatigue is impossible to fight, and at some point within the dusk period, a person within the level will succumb to the inevitability that is sleep. They will experience unconscious oblivion for the rest of the timeframe, until the night period. At that point, the person will begin to dream.

The dream experienced by the sleeping individual will last for the full 4-hour night period. During this period, the person cannot wake, and will instead conjure a detailed dream world in which lucid dreaming is not possible. In the absence of lucidity, the dreamer will piece together an amalgamate, akin to a particularly intense fever dream. In this fever dream, one's mind will create a scenario of what has been described as "the worst atrocity your mind can think of." People who have experienced this phenomenon report acting in ways which they would never act in if lucid, often describing their dream-selves as violent and unstable.

The dreamer will believe themself to have woken within the first thirty minutes of the 8-hour dawn period, but this is a falsification. Instead, their consciousness will be imprisoned in the Mindscape.

<center><span style="font-family:Pacifico"><span style="color:black; font-size:25px">The Mindscape</span></span></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
The Mindscape is that of the aforementioned Dreamwalker, who will be later discussed, and it takes a similar form to what the level would have looked like prior to one's rest. It bears the same physical constitution, save for the manner in which all the lights fail to function. However, all of the windows are lit up with a blinding light, bright to the point that it becomes unbearable to remain in the sunrooms. Due to the Mindscape not physically existing in reality, it is impossible to photograph, so no image of this place has been included.

Upon arrival here, one will experience extreme cognitive dissonance and remorse for the actions of their dream-self. Combined with the experience of just having dreamed up a horrible event, the wanderer in question will likely be in an immense amount of distress. Panic, however, is the second-greatest killer within this level; above all else, it is advised to keep one's wits about them. Panic clouds one's senses, and reality is unstable enough in this place without one's own perception betraying them.

The Mindscape is far less stable than the physical '''Level 929''', being subject to the whims of the Dreamwalker. It is known to shift, fragment, and distort without warning-- often with the intent to restrain or injure. However, the Mindscape alone cannot kill a person; one within a dream has to die by the Dreamwalker's spear.
<center><span style="font-family:Pacifico"><span style="color:black; font-size:25px">The Dreamwalker</span></span></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
{{Blurimage|file=Dreamwalker.jpg|caption=A young woman who survived Level 929 was asked to draw her experiences. This is what she provided [[M.E.G.]] interviewers.}}
The Dreamwalker is an entity that seems to have chosen '''Level 929''' as its domain. Its biology is not fully understood, as it has not been captured for study or autopsy, but since it has never been seen physically it can be cautiously presumed to be an apparition of sorts that prefers to present itself outside of conventional reality. It has full control over the Mindscape, manipulating its reality at will as previously discussed.

Despite a lack of a corporeal form making them impossible to photograph, descriptions and artist renditions of the Dreamwalker do exist. They are described as a figure with greyed skin pulled tight over their bones, draped in a hooded cloak that stops where their shins do. They drag chains behind them by their ankles, and a manacle around their neck bears another chain that connects to an incomplete mock halo of the same material over their head. They lack arms in the conventional sense, instead having floating forearms and hands connected to their body by chains. Their hair is dark and wiry, falling into disordered shapes, and they bear two glowing orbs set into their face as opposed to conventional eyes. They have no mouth, but have been reported as manipulating the Mindscape's reality to project their thoughts into the realm of perceivable stimuli. They have been seen carrying a spear made of dark metal, the grip of which is comprised of cracked laurel wood.

<span style="background:linear-gradient(white, rgba(255,255,255,0)); -webkit-background-clip:text !important; -webkit-text-fill-color:transparent;">The Dreamwalker hunts with precision and false righteousness...</span>

<div style="background-color: #0a0a0a; border: 3px solid #bdacd1; padding: 15px; color: #ffffff; box-shadow: 0 0 15px #bdacd1; font-family: monospace;">
==== <span style="color:#bdacd1;"><span style="font-family:Pacifico">That's quite enough, I believe. "False righteousness" is quite a grave accusation, wouldn't you say? I am merely a steward, with the task of culling those who fail to meet the standards of morality I have for my domain. I ask travelers to conjure the worst they can think of, to detail it extensively. I am aware it will be horrible, but the depths of human depravity are another story. I spare those whose worst doesn't cross certain lines, but some atrocities-- even in thought-- cannot be justified. To allow moral bankruptcy to run wild within my own domain would make me a rather irresponsible steward indeed. So now, I must judge my newest visitor... Rest, {{USERNAME}}.</span></span></div> ====
<br>
<choose>
<option>
<div style="background-color: #0a0a0a; border: 3px solid #bdacd1; padding: 15px; color: #ffffff; box-shadow: 0 0 15px #bdacd1; font-family: monospace;">
<span style="font-family:Kavivanar"> You are no special being, not in the slightest. You would consider yourself a good person, but have little means by which to prove this fact. Does an apple know if it is rotten? Does it feel the worms within it, feeding upon its flesh? This is an irrelevant question. You are not an apple. You are a human, and will be held to human standards. You entered Level 929 carrying with you the exhaustion and reek of sweat from the level prior. You were clearly in a bad way, so I was more than willing to allow you rest within my domain-- the least I can give a weary traveler. Perhaps you would be one of the passable humans, I hoped. I was disappointed. You had your rest until nightfall, and then you conjured up your worst. You were back in the Frontrooms, visiting family. They greeted you warmly, kindly, overjoyed to see their lost relative. And then you pulled a lighter out of the pocket of your jacket and set the house ablaze-- unwarranted, unprompted, unprovoked. Flames crawled up the walls and it was all your fault, you vengeful wraith of a human being. You told them some nonsense about how you had been forgotten, forsaken in your absence. They snapped back at you, as you deserved, and called you horrible and insane. You broke down. Your knees weakened with the weight of what you'd done. You pulled a knife off of the kitchen table and begged them to kill you. They refused, so you did it yourself. You were rotten, so I had to end you. I pulled you into my Mindscape and watched you spiral. You were distressed, of course-- you just had such a horrible dream, on top of everything else this [[Backrooms Wiki|hell-realm]] has put you through. I raised my spear. It was nothing personal. I don't despise you, {{USERNAME}}. Any death that eliminates evil is a mercy.</span></option></div>
<option>
<div style="background-color: #0a0a0a; border: 3px solid #bdacd1; padding: 15px; color: #ffffff; box-shadow: 0 0 15px #bdacd1; font-family: monospace;">
<span style="font-family:Kavivanar">When you arrived in Level 929, I had such high hopes for you. Perhaps no different from any other human, but you seemed to have a kindness in your eyes, though sad. Like snow that's begun to melt. Does frost feel woe when the sun begins to beat down upon it? This question is irrelevant. You are not snow, or frost. You are human and will be held to human standards. You were softspoken, yet so incredibly tired. Your injuries were so severe you could hardly stand, I recall. While my abilities do not include healing, I hoped to at the very least allow you a modicum of peace. Perhaps you would be one of the passable humans, I hoped, as you began to dream. You were barn with your childhood pet-- such a cute and fluffy dog. There had just been a natural disaster, and you needed to retrieve gasoline for the generator. You knocked the jug over and it sparked, and lit the spill ablaze. The flames caught in the poor creature's fur, and it screamed as it burned alive. Your worst fear is an accident causing harm to those you care about? How noble! When you woke, I offered you a tea, and consoled you through your distress.</span> </option>
<option> <span style="font-family:Kavivanar"> The manner in which you arrived, all instability and fraying nerves, concerned me. You were like a gas-fed flame-- volatile, prone to either explosion or fizzling out at a moment's notice. Do you think a flame knows when it's running out of oxygen? Do you think its last moments are desperate in their burning? This question is irrelevant. You are not a flame. You are a human, and will be held to human standards.I was certain your dream would be irredeemable, but I do give everyone who enters Level 929 a chance at proving their morality. You dreamed, as did everyone who enters my domain, but the worst you could come up with was unoriginal: slaughter, blood staining your hands and the walls in the wake of senseless violence. What a shame. I would say I do not resent you, but I despise those who cause pain without cause or even a hint of uniqueness in their choice of sin. Die and leave a more correct world in your wake, {{USERNAME}}. Die. </span></div><option>
</div></div></choose></div>

<center><span style="font-family:Pacifico"><span style="color:black; font-size:35px">Entities</span></span></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
There are no recorded entities within '''Level 929''', save for the aforementioned Dreamwalker, who seems to pride themself on maintaining a "sanctum free of moral corruption". Ironically, this is achieved through violence.

<center><span style="font-family:Pacifico"><span style="color:black; font-size:35px">Communities And Outposts</span></span></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
Due to '''Level 929'''<nowiki/>'s anomalous properties, it is not feasible to establish permanent group residences within the level. Those the Dreamwalker spares are few and far between, and their "trials" occur nightly regardless of if a person has been spared once before.
<center><span style="font-family:Pacifico"><span style="color:black; font-size:35px">Entrances And Exits</span></span></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
<center><span style="font-family:Pacifico"><span style="color:black; font-size:25px">Entrances</span></span></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
* Entering hotels in [[Level 11]] at dusk or dawn may send one here.
* Tripping over appliance cords within the houses of [[Level 912]] may send one here.
* Attempting to break some windows with particularly picturesque views in [[Level 5]] may send one here.
<center><span style="font-family:Pacifico"><span style="color:black; font-size:25px">Exits</span></span></center>
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
* It is theorized that breaking a window and leaping out of it may send one to [[the Void]].
* Noclipping into out-of-place concrete walls may send one to [[Level 948]].
* Noclipping into chairs may send one to [[Level 981]].
